  "slug": "croquembouche",
  "title": "Croquembouche",
  "subtitle": "French profiterole tower with caramel and spun sugar",
  "excerpt": "The classic French celebration centrepiece: choux profiteroles filled with crème pâtissière, dipped in caramel, and stacked into a tall cone shape, then finished with threads of spun sugar. Each component is achievable separately; the challenge is the caramel work, which must be used immediately before it sets. The cone can be built against a cardboard template for the first time. The name means 'crunch in the mouth'.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Croquembouche is documented in French pastry literature from the early nineteenth century. Marie-Antoine Carême, Le Pâtissier Royal Parisien (1815, public domain), describes the croquembouche cone as a standard French confectionery centrepiece. The format using choux profiteroles, crème pâtissière, and caramel is described in detail in French pâtisserie manuals published before 1928, including those by Jules Gouffé (Le Livre de Pâtisserie, 1873) and Alfred Suzanne.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A croquembouche needs organisation more than skill. Make the choux and crème pâtissière ahead. On the day, use ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "hot caramel as the adhesive",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Using caramel to assemble croquembouche",
                  "termId": "cmppnlop30000gsv4mljoak8x"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " to build the cone. Keep a bowl of iced water close for accidental caramel contact. Have everything in place before the caramel is ready.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
